-----<br>
“Ion drives can achieve any exhaust velocity up to 99% of the speed of light given enough electric power” <br>
<br>
Response:<br>
That’s all well and good but ‘enough power’, that’s really the trick isn’t it.  Unfortunately for the ‘electrophiles” we can’t make lightweight nuclear power plants that generate the kind of power you need to develop a substantial amount of thrust for long periods of time. The Russian TOPAZ- 2 reactor has a very short operational life time of just a few months and even it doesn’t deliver enough electricity to power an ion engine that can out accelerate a farting butterfly pushing a brick.<br>
<br>
<br>
Quote:---------------------------------------------“The Nuclear electric ion engine, plasma drive, photon rocket can fire indefinitely for years, decades, centuries, or millennia at a time if the electric power source is long lived enough.”<br>
<br>
Response:<br>
Ya right! I’ll tell you what, go buy an expensive TV set and  switch it on and leave it on for ten years and see what happens. Also no known reactor type can sustain a fission reaction without refueling for more than ~ ten years or less. That is science fiction you are talking about.   <br>
 <br>
Quote:-------------------------------------------- <br>
“The only advantage ntr has is its ability to generate high thrust levels for a short time at twice the specific impulse of the best chemical propulsion systems available.”<br>
<br>
Response:<br>
Actually the PBR reactors that NASA plans to develop have three times the ISP of  a LOX + LH2 fueled rocket. Particle bed style NTR’s can  put out an ISP of 1300  at a trust to engine weight ratio of thirty to one. MITEE (PBR) Nuclear rocket engines can put out 10,000 pounds of thrust with an engine weight of just 330 pounds and thus are just what the doctor ordered for interplanetary flights.<br>
<br>
Engines like this can push a ship including a significant payload to Mars in two or three months and that is good enough for the present. Consider that first generation EPPP systems can out perform PBR style NTR’s by a factor of four and ‘light bulb’ style GNCR’s  can best NTR’S by a factor of three.  The reality is that electric propulsion systems are at the moment irrelevant. <br>
<br>
Low thrust Ion engines may have a purpose, and that purpose might just be their use as continuously operating course correction thrusters for ships that use any one of the big three propulsion schemes and I do mean NTR, GCNR, and EPPP.<br>
